comment:
IANAL but have a law degree and I followed this case with interest because of what they did to me 20 years ago. I didn't have Depp's money, so couldn't sue. The thing with libel cases in the UK is that it's the defendant that has to prove, on the balance of probability, that what they said about the plaintiff was true. It's the exact opposite of how it works in the US, which follows the same evidential burden on defamation as it does with any other tort, whereby it's the plaintiff who has to prove that what was said about them was false. Americans are usually surprised by this difference but it makes complete sense. The idea is that if you put someone on trial in the court of public opinion, you'd better make sure you can back up your allegations. In the UK, it's can be described as a "put up, or shut up" principle. In the US, anyone can say anything about anyone else without repercussions, irrespective of the harm they cause. It's easier in the UK to win a libel action than it is in the US.

Or, at least, that's how it's supposed to be. Something that shocked me with this case was just how little evidence she needed to win. The problem that JD had to contend with was a little something called stereotyping. British judges are not immune from relying upon stereotyping whenever they want to fill in some mental gaps that nobody in front of them has filled in. For example, when it was revealed that she asked to meet him after she'd gotten a restraining order out on him, the judge decided to ignore it by stating that it was not uncommon for women who had been subjected to domestic abuse to still have feelings for their abuser. This was undoubtedly true, but she couldn't prove that this was the case. The judge just decided it was a possibility. This isn't something he should have done.

For me, the event that killed her defence stone dead was a recording that JD had made of himself making a call to an aide outside a hotel or apartment demanding that he get AH out because SHE'D just hit HIM five or six times. The entire crux of her allegations against him was that he had regularly assaulted her and that she had been in fear of her life. No woman in fear of their lives from an abuser would hit their abuser without knowledge of the potential consequences. And no serial abuser would have simply taken it like Depp did. She effectively said that he needed to man up. It was kind of a "I hit you, so what?" moment from her. And nowhere in that recording does she ask "how many times have you hit me?" Or even mention any assaults by him on her. And yet, the judge simply dismissed it. I was steaming when I read the judgment.

JD wasn't exactly the greatest witness. He made the mistake of lying a couple of times. She was much more assured in court but, in my experience, women are far better liars. It's often only after a trial that a woman's lies start to unravel but by that time it's too late.

If he wins in the US, where defamation cases are supposedly harder to win, it will be a damning indictment of the British legal system.
